BEGIN_PGML
One of the tires on your car looks a little flat. You measure its air pressure and are alarmed to see it so low at [`[$start]\text{.}`] You have a portable device that can pump air into the tire increasing the pressure at a rate of [`[$speed]\text{.}`] How long will it take to fill the tire to the manual's recommended pressure of [`[$end]\text{?}`]

[_]{$time}{20}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
This is a rate scenario. The air pressure starts out at [`[$initial]\text{,}`] and increases with a rate of [`[$rate]\text{.}`] Eventually the pressure reaches [`[$final]\text{.}`] So the equation we set up is:

[```[$initial]+[$rate]t=[$final]```]

where [`t`] is the number of minutes the pump runs. Now we follow the standard steps to solve this equation.

[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
[$initial]+[$rate]t \amp= [$final]\\
[$initial]+[$rate]t-[$initial] \amp= [$final]-[$initial]\\
[$rate]t \amp= [$final-$initial]\\
\frac{[$rate]t}{[$rate]} \amp= \frac{[$final-$initial]}{[$rate]}\\
t \amp = [$solution]
\end{aligned}
```]

So it will take [`[$time]`] for the pump to fill the tire.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

